t5283.text: But you’re right buddy. I’m so super privileged because of this. I’m only slightly inconvenienced. It’s not like I have to spend my whole life thinking of these things. Nope I definitely don’t. I wouldn’t understand what that was like.

t5284.text: Or do I leave it behind and put myself in pain? When I do that, I end up paying for it for days. I’m in too much pain to do anything. A lot of times, that’s the option I take because there are some things I can’t miss.

t5285.text: My power chair can fold but it might have trouble fitting in smaller cars. That leaves me with a few options. Do I stay behind because it’s too painful and I can’t go without my wheelchair? Do I take it even though there is a risk the driver might cancel?

t5286.text: There are days when I need my wheelchair to go out. However, it’s not easy to do that. We have one wheelchair accessible Uber in my city. A single. Solitary. Lone. Car. Trying to get that is a pain in the arse. Can you imagine if there was only one Uber in your town?

t5287.text: If multiple drivers cancel on me, I’ll be late anyway. I’ve missed trains because of this and it put my whole day out of whack. Then, there’s The matter of whether or not I take my wheelchair. I can walk but it’s painful so I don’t always do it.

t5288.text: Do you know how much planning I have to do before getting an Uber? Let me tell you. I have to leave so much earlier in case the driver cancels on me because of my service dog. It’s happened so much that I make time for it in my routine. Have you ever had to do that?
